label chapter3:

    # [Scene: Council Hall | Late Afternoon]

    scene bg ch3_98c6f2_1 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low murmur of the crowd, the hush of pages turning, a projector's quiet whir]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Tense, low strings building a steady undercurrent]
    "You step into the Council Hall carrying the leftover warmth of the rooftop garden on your skin—damp palms, the faint iron of compost in your nose—and the knot of urgency from the morning clinches again. The"
    "room smells of brass polish and stale coffee; those scents settle over you like an official coat."
    "Livia Chen sits at the dais with her exacting posture and that black bob that always reads like authority. Her trench coat is immaculate; the brooch on her lapel—an angular wave—glints. She unfolds glossy renderings across"
    "the screen: a sweeping curved seawall, a mixed-use promenade, investor logos arranged like constellations. The slides move with the mechanical certainty of a well-rehearsed argument."
    show livia_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    livia_chen "This design is immediate, comprehensive, and funded. Jobs, infrastructure, safety. We don't have the luxury of small experiments while the tide rises."
    "Her voice is practiced—warm at the edges, clinical inside. You taste the artifice like metal on your tongue. Around you, industry representatives nod; a man in a dark jacket taps the edge of his brochure like a metronome."

    "Tess O'Malley" "Funding milestones. Covenants. It's not unconditional—check the fine print on phase two."
    "You don't read it yet. You tuck the paper away. For a second you picture the rooftop garden—Grandma Hira's hands, Eli's grin—and the urge to keep those hands intact is a physical tug at your ribs."

    menu:
        "Breathe slowly and center":
            "You inhale, counting to four. Your pulse lengthens its rhythm; you let the room condense into a single, reachable point."
        "Check your wristband for the latest sensor readout":
            "The display blinks tidal graphs and a steady green; the data steadies you in its blunt honesty."
        "Look at Eli across the room":
            "Eli's fingers are threaded through his toolkit strap; his eyes meet yours and then look away—the moment holds, complicated and thin."

    # --- merge ---
    "The scene continues."
    "You take the podium after Livia finishes, the microphone catching your breath and making it too loud. Your notes are there—neat handwriting, tide charts and schematic sketches pressed flat by a thumb smudged with potting soil."
    "You can feel the room holding its breath with you. The fluorescent light casts a halo over your page, translating everything into hard edges."
    show mara_kestrel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_kestrel "Our simulations don't promise a total fix. They reduce wave energy at the neighborhoods most at risk. They keep livelihoods—fishermen, small shops—intact. They can be built with local labor, repaired by the same hands that will rely on them."
    "A murmur ripples. Grandma Hira's hand clasps the edge of her shawl; her face is taut with a plea you don't need to parse. Rafi stands at the back like an old mast—steady, solid—nodding once."

    "Industry Rep" "With respect, those are pilot projects. Pilots in the face of escalating storms are compromises you can't afford."
    "You hear the accusation in his tone—an implied moral failing. You counter with statistics, with sensitivity analyses that show how distributed measures change flood line projections by measurable margins in plausible scenarios. You lay out the maintenance plans, the training programs, the phased cost curves."
    "But the chamber remembers other rules—speed, scale, the siren call of capital. Livia rises, the slide behind her switching to a glossy rendering of a thriving promenade and an numbers board that reads like an investor pitch."

    livia_chen "Scale saves people quickly. The shore needs a decisive, unified barrier. Fragmented solutions cost more in the long run; they delay action."
    "You sense the tightness under her words now—a microtremor—like a wave under an iron plate. For the first time in public, her control shows a hairline crack: a brief hard set at the corner of her"
    "mouth, a finger that lingers on the slide advancer longer than necessary. One of Tess's notes flutters in your memory: covenant strings. You can't tell if that string will hold the promise or pull the whole"
    "town apart."
    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan rises after you. He walks to the microphone with the casual certainty of someone who has built things from scrap and made them sing. His voice is bright—open, but with an edge that carries the weight of scars."

    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan" "This isn't either-or. You can put a seawall where it makes sense and—' (he glances at Livia) '—but you also have to keep the neighborhoods functioning, the crews employed, the knowledge passed on. If we outsource everything to a wall, where do the people go when the wall fails?"
    "There is a shift in the room. A few heads tilt; some councilors exchange glances. Eli's words land like a small hammer on a brittle surface and it cracks enough for sound to move through."

    livia_chen "Mr. Rowan, what you propose sounds—idealistic. The council has to think in population protection. Logistics. One coordinated barrier is administratively simpler."

    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan" "Simpler for whom?' (he looks at the audience, then at you) 'For the contractors, perhaps. For the people who live here, simpler can mean abandonment."
    "The exchange grows teeth. A woman with a campaign lapel — a backer of Livia's plan — coughs loudly; someone shouts for 'jobs.' Grandma Hira stands now, and when she speaks her voice is small but sharpened by history."
    show grandma_hira at center:
        zoom 0.7

    grandma_hira "I have seen the boardwalk swallowed once. We sang while we mended it. We buried the ones the water took. You tell me to move every time. When do we keep what we love?"
    "Her question lands like a bell. The room tightens. The air tastes faintly of salt and fear."
    "You find yourself parsing motives like sea charts. Livia genuinely believes in order through scale; Tess's notes suggest legal levers that can bind the promise; Rafi's posture says he will show up to build; Eli's earnestness"
    "is tempered by past mistakes he barely mentions. You feel, underneath everything, the fragile thing that lives between you and Eli—trust that might hold or fray depending on the choice you make."

    "Council Chair" "Ms. Kestrel, the council looks to you for a recommendation. Your models and experience are central. The town needs a path forward. Speak plainly."
    "You can feel the gallery pressing inward—rows of faces that have stories folded into their skin. The room is a physical weight: the brass reflecting the light like cold scales, the ocean beyond the windows a flat, indifferent witness."
    "A flurry of rapid exchanges erupts as councilors seek clarification—line items, maintenance responsibilities, insurance clauses. Voices overlap; the projector hums louder. The tempo rises; your pulse keeps perfect tempo with it. You count the breaths without meaning to. Each second stretches and compresses."

    menu:
        "Lean into the data — make a clinical, hard argument":
            "You force your voice into the cadence of the lab: precise, unromantic. The room listens for certainty; some appreciate it, others recoil at the dryness."
        "Tell Grandma Hira's story first — anchor the policy in people":
            "You let emotion lace your words. Faces soften; some councilors shift uncomfortably, unsure whether to be moved or pragmatic."

    # --- merge ---
    "The scene continues."
    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan steps forward, placing a hand briefly near your elbow—not touching, but close enough that the heat of his presence reads as an offering and a question. You look at him. There is so"
    "much that could fracture if you misstep: trust with a partner, trust with a town, trust with a history that refuses to be measured only in spreadsheets."
    "Livia watches you with that calibrated gaze. For the first time her smile is not quite gentle; it is an assessment. Her next words are lower, a steel wire beneath velvet."

    livia_chen "Ms. Kestrel, your models are compelling in controlled conditions. The reality is messier. The council needs a plan that politics and markets will fund without years of piloting. We can begin construction this season. Delay risks lives."
    "You bite a thought back. The word 'delay' becomes a blade that slices through every softer alternative. You feel the room pivot between fear of inaction and fear of wrong action. The air is charged—electric, too tight to hold without snapping."
    hide livia_chen
    show rafi_gmez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rafi_gmez "We've weathered storms together. We can learn to fix our own seams. But we need the tools and the rights to work. Don't hand us a promise that locks us out."
    "An industry rep scoffs; a young councilor whispers about ballots and polls. The noise is a swarm."
    "Your throat is dry. The projector blinks. Somewhere beyond the windows the sea presses the horizon like an accusation."

    "Council Chair" "This chamber needs a resolution. The vote will follow your recommendation, Ms. Kestrel. How do you advise we proceed?"
    "You inhale. The whole room holds its breath with you. Your heart hammers like a signal drum in a gale. Everything you have worked for—your notebooks, the rooftop, the people who taught you how to read"
    "tide lines—presses close. So does the person on the benches whose hands you have come to find steady in the dark."
    "You can already feel the consequences as possible futures, each tugging at a different seam of your life and the town's fabric: a street-level movement bound in the dirt and calluses of neighbors; a sweeping contract"
    "that could secure funding but estrange the people who trusted you; or a brittle hybrid that makes you the hinge, admired and targeted in equal measure."
    "The chamber tightens to a single point. The projector fades to a blank white while the council waits on your next words."
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: String tension crescendos, then cuts to a single sustained note]
    "You are aware, with the precise clarity of someone standing on a cliff, that whatever you choose now will not simply be a policy. It will be a promise—or a wound—to the town, to Eli, to yourself."
    "You swallow and prepare to speak."

    menu:
        "I back a community-led, decentralized resilience plan.":
            jump chapter4
        "I endorse Livia's large-scale seawall to secure immediate funding.":
            jump chapter7
        "I propose a negotiated hybrid — a pilot community program tied to development covenants.":
            jump chapter10
